result.execSummary:
The defendant Abigail Baez was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property >$2500-$5000 [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).
  • Battery, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: The Court ordered restitution in the stipulated amount of $75.00 payable to Aaron R.--to be paid first and within the first year of probation period. Restitution is join and several with any co-actors ultimately convicted and sentenced in this matter (cases 14CF293-14CF296).

Pay applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs by the end of probation period--any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment. Pay all supervision fees. If revoked, the Court ordered all financial obligations and restitution to be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of prison funds and as a condition of extended supervision. Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.

Obtain GED or HSED.
Obtain/maintain full time employment or full time school with part time employment.
Defendant is informed she may not possess and/or own any firearms.

No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause.
No contact with victims Nicolas F., Aaron R., Alexandre J-S., Elizabeth L., Karissa H., Mitchell H. and co-actors Mary Molale, Willmarvin Diaz-Boria, Jeriel Rodriguez, and Erik Tejada.

Absolute sobriety with screens as to drugs and alcohol.
Cooperate with all rules set forth by the probation agent.
Participate in Cognitive Thinking Program.
Provide DNA sample--pay surcharge.
Defendant is informed she may not vote in any election until her civil rights have been reinstated. 
Defense motion for explungement heard and granted by the court contingent upon successful completion of all conditions of probation (i.e. no violations, pay all costs and restitution, obtain GED, etc.)
Obtain AODA assessment and if necessary, complete follow-up care/treatment.

Consecutive to: Count 3 and to any other sentence with credit for 7 days time served.

Defendant Abigail Baez in court with Attorney Susan M Roth.  Benjamin A Wesson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

On motion of the State, Court ordered Count 3 amended to:
Count 3:  THEFT, PTAC- As a Party to a Crime, contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 943.20(1)(a) & (3)(b)(f), a Class I Felony
Count 4:  Battery, PTAC- As a Party to a Crime, contrary to Wisconsin Statutes section(s) 940.19(1), a Class A Misdemeanor

The defendant was advised of her constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum to Plea Questionnaire, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.  Filed, Ineligible Voting Notice and Acknowledgement.  
  Sentencing hearing scheduled for May 29, 2014 at 08:30 am.
